      <div class="ians-column">
        <p>In this section we are going to consider what it means to learn, how we learn and what factors may influence a student’s ability to learn.</p>
        <p>To start, let’s have a look at our <strong>definition</strong> of learning:</p>

      </div>

      <div class="oj-full-width-question">
        <div class="ians-column-wide-3">
          <p>A relatively permanent change in behaviour, brought about by an experience.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="oj-hero"></div>

      <div class="ians-column mt-12">

        <p>Please read the two stories below and decide, based on our definition, if learning has taken place:</p>

      </div>

      <div class="ians-column-double ians-grid-2 oj-stories-container">

        <div>
          <h3>A&nbsp;Scotsman&nbsp;Abroad</h3>

          {% image "images/sunburn.jpg", "Photo of man at the beach with sunburn and an anguished look on his face.",
				"oj-photo-sunburn" %}

          <div class="oj-stories-content">

            <p>A Scotsman travels to Spain for his <strong>first ever</strong> summer vacation abroad. He’s very excited to get to the beach! Unfortunately, <strong>sun cream</strong> was not an item he thought to include in his travel bag. After the <strong>painful</strong> experience of the first day out, lying on a beach in the Spanish sun, he quickly (although belatedly) decided to change his daily routine. After a visit to the local pharmacy for some factor 50+ sun cream and a sun hat, he spent <strong>each morning</strong> covering himself with sun cream before venturing outside.</p>

            <p>The following year, this Scotsman decides that he will go back to Spain for another beach holiday. The <strong>first</strong> things he puts into his suitcase are his sun hat and sun cream.</p>

            <iframe class="oj-question" src="https://trainingzone.h5p.com/content/1291432388631983777/embed" width="10" height="10" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen="allowfullscreen" allow="geolocation *; microphone *; camera *; midi *; encrypted-media *"></iframe>

            <p>But, what if he had decided that the <strong>experience</strong> was so horrible that he would never again take a sunny beach holiday? He would never have a need for sun cream again and is likely to simply forget about it because it has no impact on his life.  So what learning has taken place? In fact, a behaviour <strong>has been learnt</strong> – he has learnt to avoid sunny beach holidays and so any time he sees advertisements for holidays with sandy beaches and sun, he practices the behaviour of avoidance.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div>
          <h3>An&nbsp;OJTI&nbsp;in&nbsp;the&nbsp;making</h3>

          {% image "images/oleks.jpg", "Photo of man entering an office.",
				"oj-photo-angela" %}

          <div class="oj-stories-content">

            <p>Jon arrives at EUROCONTROL ALC to start the <strong>practical</strong> part of the OJTI course. He learns <strong>specific</strong> operational <strong>procedures</strong> for the airspace that is used during <strong>simulations</strong> on the course that are very different to the ones he uses back home. As part of the course, he <strong>practiced</strong> delivering briefings and debriefings to ‘students’ using the airspace and procedures in the simulation.</p>

            <p>Jon then <strong>goes back</strong> to his <strong>operational unit</strong>. He now delivers briefings and debriefings to students and instructs using the operational procedures of his unit.</p>

            <iframe class="oj-question" src="https://trainingzone.h5p.com/content/1291432393934684487/embed" width="10" height="10" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen="allowfullscreen" allow="geolocation *; microphone *; camera *; midi *; encrypted-media *"></iframe>

            <p>But what of the procedures he had to use while in the simulator? Having returned to his operational unit, he promptly <strong>forgot</strong> them as he had no need of them. In this case, the change of behaviour was very <strong>short-lived</strong> and so does <strong>not</strong> fit our definition of ‘learning’. </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="ians-column">

        <p>The definition we use has a number of implications for instructing in the operational environment, that we should be aware of:</p>

        <ol class="list-disc list-inside">
          <li>A change in behaviour can be both <strong>good or bad</strong> in terms of <strong>safety, efficiency, cooperation</strong> and so on. As instructors it is our job to guide the learner towards ‘good’ behaviours.</li>
          <li>The change in behaviour is relatively <strong>permanent</strong>, meaning that competence as a controller is only achieved once the trainee is routinely and consistently demonstrating the required behaviours.</li>
          <li>Learning is brought about by <strong>‘experiences’</strong>. These experiences are varied and may happen directly through exposure and practice in a particular airspace (simulated or live) but are also supplemented through observation or indirectly (e.g. reading, classroom lessons, online learning, etc.)</li>
          <li>Learning is not restricted to planned learning events. ATCOs will continue to learn and modify their behaviour <strong>throughout their careers</strong>.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2>The Learning Curve</h2>

        <p>When learning takes place, as an instructor it is worth bearing in mind that different trainees will <strong>learn at different speeds</strong>. The speed and pace at which someone learns something is their learning curve and it can <strong>vary</strong> from activity to activity, and be influenced by many different factors, which we will talk about later.</p>

