        <h2>Different learning styles</h2>

        <p>A well-designed training course will allow a trainee to <strong>build up</strong> the knowledge, skills and competencies needed to do the job in a logical and systematic way. The <strong>structure</strong> that is put in place ensures that the trainee can <strong>connect</strong> the relevant pieces of knowledge and use the knowledge to build skills, perform tasks and demonstrate competence.</p>

        <p>Some trainees prefer a <strong>building block</strong> approach; they first need foundational knowledge and then they can build up the next layer of knowledge and skills and progress stepwise towards competence. These learners are typically called <strong>‘serialistic learners’</strong>. </p>

        <p>There are some learners, who prefer a more <strong>‘holistic’</strong> approach to learning. They need to understand the <strong>big picture</strong> of what they are trying to achieve and then are comfortable with working at many different levels at the same time, confident that in the end it will all start to connect.</p>

        <p>In practice, <strong>no trainee</strong> is 100% a serialist or holistic learner. UTP design and instructors, switch between holistic and serialistic learning. There are times when it is most beneficial to give an overview of what is to be achieved, and there are times when it makes sense to take a stepwise approach to the learning. As an instructor, you will learn when to do this switching.</p>

        <p>In addition, as an instructor it is worth <strong>paying attention</strong> to the way in which trainees take in information and use it to learn. Broadly speaking there are three ways that trainees do this. Bear in mind that although one of the styles may dominate, <strong>everyone uses all the modalities</strong> at various stages of learning.</p>

